"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:5.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">5.2</span> Lampstand</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מְנוֹרָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mnorah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs4:10\">2KI 4:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech4:2\">ZEC 4:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech4:11\">ZEC 4:11</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Aramaic</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">נֶבְרְשָׁה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(nevrshah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan5:5\">DAN 5:5</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">λυχνία</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(luchnia)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:15\">MAT 5:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark4:21\">MRK 4:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke8:16\">LUK 8:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke11:33\">LUK 11:33</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev1:13\">REV 1:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev1:20\">REV 1:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev1:20\">REV 1:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev2:1\">REV 2:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev2:5\">REV 2:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev11:4\">REV 11:4</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/UBS-0029_lampstand.jpg\" alt=\"Lampstands\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Lampstands (© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart by United Bible Societies)</figcaption></figure>The lampstand was a stand designed to hold a single lamp or a series of lamps. It could be made of a variety of materials and took various shapes and sizes. Its purpose was to raise the light higher than the level of the floor or table and so light a larger area. For the lampstand in the Tabernacle, see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">4.3.4 Lampstand, menorah&lt;REALIA:4.3.4&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0941_oil_lamps.jpg\" alt=\"Oil lamps\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Oil lamps (© Zde Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>Since there is no special word for “lampstand” in many cultures, this may have to be translated “lamp holder,” “thing on which lamps are placed,” or “place for putting lamps.” Where the translator has chosen to render the oil lamp as “candle,” the appropriate word for a candleholder could be used.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan5:5\">DAN 5:5</a>: The writing on the wall is said to have been “opposite the lampstand” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>). This would be in the most clearly illuminated part of the banquet hall. This should probably be stated clearly in most languages. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> has “where the light from the lamps was shining most brightly.” Also possible is “where the light was strongest” or “where people could see very clearly.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
